The workflow ensures accurate transaction analysis and fraud prediction.

7. Dataset Description

The dataset used for this project contains historical credit card transaction records.

Dataset Features

Typical features include:

Transaction Time
Transaction Amount
Anonymized Features (V1 to V28)
Transaction Class Label

Where:

0 = Genuine Transaction
1 = Fraudulent Transaction

The dataset is highly imbalanced because fraudulent transactions represent only a very small percentage of total transactions.

8. Data Preprocessing

Data preprocessing is one of the most important stages in machine learning.

Steps Performed
Removal of duplicate records
Handling missing values
Feature scaling
Data normalization
Data balancing
Train-test split
Data Balancing Techniques

Fraud datasets are usually imbalanced. Common balancing methods include:

SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique)
Undersampling
Oversampling

These methods improve model performance.

9. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

EDA helps understand transaction behavior and fraud patterns.

Analysis Performed
Fraud vs Genuine transaction distribution
Correlation heatmaps
Transaction amount analysis
Time-based fraud trends
Outlier detection

Visualization tools help identify suspicious patterns effectively.

10. Machine Learning Algorithms Used
Logistic Regression

A simple and efficient algorithm used for binary classification.

Advantages
Fast execution
Good baseline model
Easy implementation
Random Forest

An ensemble learning algorithm that improves prediction accuracy.

Advantages
Handles large datasets
Reduces overfitting
High accuracy
Decision Tree

Used to classify transactions based on transaction patterns.

Advantages
Easy interpretation
Fast predictions
XGBoost (Optional Advanced Model)

Advanced boosting algorithm for high-performance fraud detection.

Advantages
Excellent accuracy
Handles imbalance efficiently
Optimized performance

11. Model Training Process

The model training process includes:

Importing the dataset
Splitting training and testing data
Applying preprocessing
Training ML models
Evaluating performance metrics
Saving trained model

The trained model is saved using Pickle for deployment.

12. Model Evaluation Metrics

The following metrics are used:

Metric	Purpose
Accuracy	Overall prediction correctness
Precision	Correct fraud predictions
Recall	Detection of actual fraud cases
F1-Score	Balance between precision and recall
ROC-AUC Score	Model discrimination capability

Fraud detection systems focus heavily on Recall because missing fraudulent transactions can lead to financial loss.

